 name for someone who lived on land that had been cleared, from Old High German <i>rod</i>, Middle English <i>roth(e)</i> (Old English <i>roth</i>) ‘clearing’. In England, the name may also be a habitational name from any of the places like Rothend in Ashdon (Essex), Roe End in Markyate (Hertfordshire), Roe Green in Hatfield (Hertfordshire), or Roe Green in Sandon (Hertfordshire).","German: from a short form of any of various ancient Germanic personal names with the first element <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’. Compare   Rode   1,   Ross   4."],"variants":[{"name":"Rother","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Hans, Heinz, Elke, Florian, Franz, Gerda, Konrad, Lotti, Reinhard.","German:","nickname for a person with red hair, from an inflected form of   Roth   1."]},{"name":"Rothe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Achim, Dietmar, Erhard, Franz, Friede, Heinrich, Helmut, Inge, Klaus, Siegfried, Wolfram.","German:","variant of   Roth   1."]},{"name":"Roat","meanings":["Probably an Americanized form of German   Roth  .","English (Kent and Middlesex): variant of   Root  ."]},{"name":"Rothmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Heinrich, Heinz.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for a person with red hair, from an elaborated form of   Roth   1 with the addition of Middle High German, Yiddish <i>man</i> (German <i>Mann</i>) ‘man’. Compare   Rothman   and   Redman  .","German: topographic name for someone who lived on land that had been cleared, from an elaborated form of   Roth   2 with the addition of Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Rode","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Erwin, Ewald, Hans, Heinz, Oskar, Viktor, Claus, Frieda, Fritz, Gerhard, Horst.","German and French: from a short form of any of various ancient Germanic personal names with the first element <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’. Compare   Robert  ,   Rudiger  .","North German, Danish, and English: topographic name for someone who lived on land cleared for cultivation or in a clearing in woodland, from Middle Low German <i>rode</i>, Danish <i>rothe</i>, Old English <i>rod</i>. There are a number of places in England named with this word, for example Rode in Cheshire, and the surname may derive from any of these. Compare   Rhode  ."]},{"name":"Rote","meanings":["Perhaps an Americanized form of German   Roth   or   Rothe  .","English: variant of   Root  ."]},{"name":"Rothell","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Röthel</b>, a diminutive of   Roth   1, or a habitational name from a place so named in Switzerland."]},{"name":"Rauth","meanings":["South German: from Middle High German <i>(ge)riute</i> ‘clearing’, hence a topographic name for someone who lived in a clearing or occupational name for a clearer of woodland, or a habitational name from a place so named in Bavaria.","Americanized form of German   Roth   or   Rath  ."]},{"name":"Roethel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Reinhold, Albrecht, Dieter, Gerhard, Guenther, Helmut, Wilhelm.","German (<b>Röthel</b>): diminutive of   Roth  ."]},{"name":"Roath","meanings":["Probably an Americanized form of German   Roth  .","English (Warwickshire): nickname from Middle English <i>wrothe</i> ‘angry, fierce, bold’ (Old English <i>wrāth</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Erline","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently a feminine derivative of   Erle ."],"variants":[{"name":"Earla","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: coined as a feminine form of   Earl ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":18,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictio